{{globalize/Canada|date=December 2008}}
A '''Chemist In Training''' ('''CIT''') is a [[Canada|Canadian]] designation for someone who has obtained a [[academic degree|degree]] from an accredited institution that qualifies for registration with one of the provincial or territorial chemical professional associations,<ref>http://www.pchem.ca</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ocq.qc.ca/fr/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-12-23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090102101620/http://www.ocq.qc.ca/fr/ |archivedate=2009-01-02 |df= }}</ref><ref>http://www.acpo.on.ca/</ref> but has not yet achieved the additional requirements (like relevant supervised work experience) to become accredited as a [[Professional Chemist]] (P.Chem.).
==Licensure== A licensed CIT is certified to work in a [[chemistry]] profession. Upon completing a certain amount of work experience under the supervision of a Licensed Professional Chemist (P.Chem.) as determined by a [[licensing board]],<ref>http://www.pchem.ca</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ocq.qc.ca/fr/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-12-23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090102101620/http://www.ocq.qc.ca/fr/ |archivedate=2009-01-02 |df= }}</ref><ref>http://www.acpo.on.ca/</ref> a CIT is then eligible to gain experience by supervision from a P.Chem.
While being a certified CIT may help in obtaining a chemistry related job, it is not typically required to do chemistry work. All work performed by an CIT must still be checked and certified by a P.Chem.
